LXXIII. ¹ Simul et invisum et offensum sibi parum idoneum, &c.] There is nota stop in this sentence in the edition sent to me from Rome. Invisum is the reading in it, which you see in the text, it is invitum in the edition of Cortius and others, which does not make good sense. Cot-tius explains it, Invitus erat cum Metello, i. e. manebat; but see what he has obtruded into the text, which it really has not. Marius invitus, or Marius invitus est, makes no sense3 but Marius invitus mansit, or abivit, makes good. I take offensum absolutely, hostile, iuimical, &c3 and I make sibi governed by idoneum. See what differcuce of meaning the change of one letter makes.
